Background¶

https://www.kaggle.com/headsortails/us-election-2020-presidential-debates

The US 2020 election saw the incumbent Republican president Donald Trump facing off against his Democrat challenger Joe Biden. Both candidates agreed to debate their political stances in the lead-up to the vote on November 3rd.

The 1st debate took place on September 29th at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland, Ohio. It was moderated by Fox News anchor Chris Wallace.

After Donald Trump tested positive for Covid-19 after his first debate and subsequently recovered, the 2nd presidential debate was initially converted into a virtual event. However, Trump declined to participate in a virtual debate and the event was transformed into a (socially distanced) town hall with Joe Biden alone. This event was moderated by George Stephanopoulos on the ABC network and took place on October 15th. Donald Trump then decided to hold a town hall of his own, which took place at the same day and time as the Biden town hall and was aired on NBC. This event was moderated by Savannah Guthrie.

The actual 2nd, and final, presidential debate between Biden and Trump took place on October 22nd at Belmont University, Nashville, Tennessee and was moderated by NBC News' Kristen Welker. This debate implemented stricter conditions on the candidates' speaking times to limit the frequent interruptions that had characterised the 1st debate.

The goal of this homework assignment is to investigate the transcripts of those events.

The data files are available via https://github.com/umsi-data-science/data/tree/main/us_election_2020. Note that each file is available in two formats: CSV and TXT. You can work from either format -- the content of the corresponding CSV and TXT files is the same.

You can either use the correct URLs to the Raw version of the data files like we've done with other data files in the course so far, you can clone the repo if you're comfortable with git, or you can click on each file and then view the "Raw" format and download the resulting file. You do not need the us_election_2020_vice_presidential_debate files as we are only concerned with the presidential debates and town halls for this assignment.

Note that you will need to make decisions about how you proceed with the analysis. For example, you will need to decide whether you include or omit stopwords, whether you stem or lemmatize words before analysis, and how you handle weird situations.

You will need to decide when to exclude speech from the moderators and when to include it (note that in most cases, the assignment asks about the candidates, which means Trump and Biden and not the moderators).

# Load Spacy model
nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')

# Function to preprocess text
def preprocess_text(text):
    # Tokenize text
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    # Remove punctuation
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.isalnum()]
    # Remove stopwords
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word not in stop_words]
    # Lemmatization with POS tagging
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmatized_tokens = []
    for word, tag in pos_tag(tokens):
        pos = tag[0].lower()
        pos = pos if pos in ['a', 'r', 'n', 'v'] else None
        if not pos:
            lemma = word
        else:
            lemma = lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos)
        lemmatized_tokens.append(lemma)
    return lemmatized_tokens

# Function to count words for each candidate in a debate with specific candidate names
def count_words(debate_transcript, candidate_names_debate1, candidate_names_debate2, debate_number):
    word_counts = {}
    if debate_number == 1:
        candidate_names = candidate_names_debate1
    else:
        candidate_names = candidate_names_debate2
    for candidate in candidate_names:
        candidate_text = ' '.join(debate_transcript[debate_transcript['speaker'].str.contains(candidate, case=False)]['text'])
        processed_text = preprocess_text(candidate_text)
        word_counts[candidate] = len(processed_text)
    return word_counts

# your code here...
# Function to count speaking turns
def count_speaking_turns(transcript, candidate_names):
    speaking_turns = {candidate: 0 for candidate in candidate_names}
    
    # Current speaker initialization
    current_speaker = None
    
    for index, row in transcript.iterrows():
        speaker = row['speaker']
        if speaker not in candidate_names:
            continue  # Skip if speaker is not one of the candidates
        if speaker != current_speaker:
            speaking_turns[speaker] += 1
            current_speaker = speaker
            
    return speaking_turns

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# your code here...
# extract unique nouns from a text
def extract_unique_nouns(text):
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    words = [word for word in words if word.isalpha()]  # Remove punctuation
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    words = [word for word in words if word not in stop_words]  # Remove stopwords
    tagged = pos_tag(words)
    # Extract unique nouns (NN for singular noun, NNS for plural noun)
    nouns = {word for word, tag in tagged if tag in ["NN", "NNS"]}
    return nouns

# Candidate names
debate1_candidate_names = ['President Donald J. Trump', 'Vice President Joe Biden']
debate2_candidate_names = ['Donald Trump', 'Joe Biden']

# Count unique nouns for each candidate in each debate
def count_nouns(transcript, candidate_names):
    noun_counts = {}
    for candidate in candidate_names:
        candidate_text = ' '.join(transcript[transcript['speaker'].str.contains(candidate, case=False, regex=False)]['text'])
        unique_nouns = extract_unique_nouns(candidate_text)
        noun_counts[candidate] = len(unique_nouns)
    return noun_counts

noun_counts_debate1 = count_nouns(debate1_transcript, debate1_candidate_names)
noun_counts_debate2 = count_nouns(debate2_transcript, debate2_candidate_names)

data = {

    'Second Debate': [noun_counts_debate2[debate2_candidate_names[0]], noun_counts_debate2[debate2_candidate_names[1]]]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data, index=['Trump', 'Biden'])

# Plotting
df.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10, 6))

4. Report the type-token ratio for each of the candidates (Trump & Biden), based on pooling the data from the two debates, and interpret the differences between the two candidates.¶

In text analysis, a 'type' is a unique word, whereas a 'token' is any word. For example, the sentence

"One fish, two fish, red fish, blue fish"

contains 8 tokens, but 5 types (one, two, red, blue, fish).

Interestingly, the type-token ratio can be used to monitor changes in the use of vocabulary items in children with under-developed vocabulary and/or word finding difficulties and, for example, in adults who have suffered a stroke and who consequently exhibit word retrieval difficulties and naming difficulties. Ref

In [ ]:
# calculate Type-Token Ratio (TTR)
def calculate_ttr(text):
    # Tokenize the text
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    # Create a counter of words to get unique types
    types = Counter(tokens)
    # Calculate TTR: Number of unique types divided by the total number of tokens
    ttr = len(types) / len(tokens)
    return ttr

# Combine the text for each candidate from both debates
trump_text = ' '.join(debate1_transcript[debate1_transcript['speaker'] == 'President Donald J. Trump']['text']) + ' ' + \
             ' '.join(debate2_transcript[debate2_transcript['speaker'] == 'Donald Trump']['text'])
biden_text = ' '.join(debate1_transcript[debate1_transcript['speaker'] == 'Vice President Joe Biden']['text']) + ' ' + \
             ' '.join(debate2_transcript[debate2_transcript['speaker'] == 'Joe Biden']['text'])

# Calculate TTR for each candidate
trump_ttr = calculate_ttr(trump_text)
biden_ttr = calculate_ttr(biden_text)

# Print the TTR for both candidates
print(f"Trump's Type-Token Ratio: {trump_ttr}")
print(f"Biden's Type-Token Ratio: {biden_ttr}")

Trump's Type-Token Ratio: 0.10558386300362452
Biden's Type-Token Ratio: 0.12667131728868736

The TTR for Trump is around 0.0558, the TTR for Biden is around 0.12667. Biden has a higher TTR value, which means he has a greater variety of vocabulary.Trump's lower TTR suggests that he may have repeated the use of a smaller set of words throughout the debates, resulting in a less varied vocabulary compared to Biden, which is also consistent with Q3 ’s result, Biden used more unique nouns in both debates compared to Trump.

The difference in TTR between the two candidates implies differences in their speaking styles and language use. Biden's higher TTR may reflect a broader range of ideas and expressions, while Trump's lower TTR may suggest more repetitive language patterns.

# Extract only the text spoken by Trump and Biden themselves
trump_speech = trump_text[trump_text['speaker'] == 'President Trump']['text'].str.cat(sep=' ')
biden_speech = biden_text[biden_text['speaker'] == 'Joe Biden']['text'].str.cat(sep=' ')

# Function to extract entities and count them for each candidate
def extract_entities(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    entities = [ent.label_ for ent in doc.ents]
    return Counter(entities)

# Extract entities for both candidates
trump_entities = extract_entities(trump_speech)
biden_entities = extract_entities(biden_speech)

def plot_entity_distribution(entities, candidate_name):
    # Sort entities by count
    sorted_entities = dict(sorted(entities.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
    
    # Create the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    plt.bar(sorted_entities.keys(), sorted_entities.values())
    plt.title(f'Named Entity Distribution for {candidate_name}')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.xlabel('Entity Types')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.show()

# Plot the entity distributions for Trump
plot_entity_distribution(trump_entities, "Trump")

# Plot the entity distributions for Biden
plot_entity_distribution(biden_entities, "Biden")

In the bar charts, for Trump, the most frequent named entity type was 'GPE' (countries, cities, etc.), followed by 'DATE' and 'PERSON'. This suggests a focus on geographical and temporal elements, as well as discussions involving specific individuals. The presence of 'CARDINAL' and 'ORG' also implies a quantitative aspect to his discussions and mentions of various organizations.

Biden's chart shows a higher frequency of 'CARDINAL' entities, indicating a strong emphasis on numbers and quantitative data in his speech. He also frequently mentioned 'ORG' and 'DATE', much like Trump. However, the 'GPE' count for Biden is lower compared to Trump, suggesting a possible difference in the geographical scope or focus of their discussions.

For both charts, there are relatively low occurrences of 'MONEY', 'PERCENT', 'LAW', 'FAC' (facilities), 'LOC' (locations), and 'EVENT', suggesting these were not the main points of discussion for either candidate.

import numpy as np
from textblob import TextBlob

def get_polarity(text):
    return TextBlob(text).sentiment.polarity

def get_subjectivity(text):
    return TextBlob(text).sentiment.subjectivity

# Apply these functions to the text column of the dataframe
debate2_transcript['Polarity'] = debate2_transcript['text'].apply(get_polarity)
debate2_transcript['Subjectivity'] = debate2_transcript['text'].apply(get_subjectivity)

# Now, we will separate the data for each candidate
trump_debate2 = debate2_transcript[debate2_transcript['speaker'] == 'Donald Trump']
biden_debate2 = debate2_transcript[debate2_transcript['speaker'] == 'Joe Biden']

# Let's calculate the rolling average of the sentiment polarity over the course of the debate
trump_debate2['Rolling_Polarity'] = trump_debate2['Polarity'].rolling(10,min_periods=1).mean()
biden_debate2['Rolling_Polarity'] = biden_debate2['Polarity'].rolling(10,min_periods=1).mean()

# Plotting the sentiment over time for each candidate
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.plot(trump_debate2['minute'], trump_debate2['Rolling_Polarity'], label='Trump')
plt.plot(biden_debate2['minute'], biden_debate2['Rolling_Polarity'], label='Biden')
plt.title('Rolling Average Sentiment Polarity During the 2nd Presidential Debate')
plt.xlabel('Time (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Sentiment Polarity')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
